```{r load-and-clean, include=FALSE}
# ── Load data ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# UCI Heart Disease dataset (all four sites):
# https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/45/heart+disease
url <- "https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/heart-disease/processed.cleveland.data"

col_names <- c("age","sex","cp","trestbps","chol","fbs","restecg",
               "thalach","exang","oldpeak","slope","ca","thal","num")

# Cleveland only
cleveland_raw <- read.csv(
  url, header = FALSE, col.names = col_names, na.strings = "?"
)

# All four sites combined (manually assembled by UCI)
sites <- c(
  "https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/heart-disease/processed.cleveland.data",
  "https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/heart-disease/processed.hungarian.data",
  "https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/heart-disease/processed.switzerland.data",
  "https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/heart-disease/processed.va.data"
)

all_raw <- map_dfr(sites, ~ {
  read.csv(.x, header = FALSE, col.names = col_names, na.strings = "?")
})

# ── Cleaning helper ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
clean_heart <- function(df) {
  df %>%
    mutate(
      heart_disease = if_else(num > 0, 1L, 0L),  # binary outcome
      chol     = if_else(chol    <= 0, NA_real_, as.numeric(chol)),
      trestbps = if_else(trestbps <= 0, NA_real_, as.numeric(trestbps))
    ) %>%
    select(heart_disease, chol, age, trestbps) %>%
    drop_na()
}

heart_cle <- clean_heart(cleveland_raw)   # n = 303
heart_all <- clean_heart(all_raw)         # n = 675

# ── Exploration / confirmation split (Cleveland only, 70/30) ───────────────────
set.seed(203)
n_cle   <- nrow(heart_cle)
exp_idx <- sample(seq_len(n_cle), size = floor(0.30 * n_cle))

heart_explore <- heart_cle[ exp_idx, ]
heart_confirm <- heart_cle[-exp_idx, ]   # ← confirmation set used in all results
```

```{r models, include=FALSE}
# ── Models (confirmation set for Cleveland; full set for all-sites) ─────────────
model1_cle <- lm(heart_disease ~ chol,                    data = heart_confirm)
model2_cle <- lm(heart_disease ~ chol + age + trestbps,   data = heart_confirm)
model1_all <- lm(heart_disease ~ chol,                    data = heart_all)
model2_all <- lm(heart_disease ~ chol + age + trestbps,   data = heart_all)

# Heteroskedasticity-robust (HC3) standard errors
se1_cle <- sqrt(diag(vcovHC(model1_cle, type = "HC3")))
se2_cle <- sqrt(diag(vcovHC(model2_cle, type = "HC3")))
se1_all <- sqrt(diag(vcovHC(model1_all, type = "HC3")))
se2_all <- sqrt(diag(vcovHC(model2_all, type = "HC3")))
```

## Introduction

Heart disease a leading cause of death in the United States, responsible for about one in five deaths each year. Serum cholesterol, which is the total amount of cholesterol in the blood, has been considered to be the leading factor for heart disease. This perception has influenced years of dietary guidelines, drug development, and clinical decisions. However, recent studies show a more complex picture, indicating that the correlation between cholesterol and heart disease weakens significantly when considering age and blood pressure (Wilson et al., 1998; Detrano et al., 1989). Understanding the relationship between cholesterol and heart disease, and how this relationship changes while accounting for common confounding factors, is important for not just policymakers, but patients as well. Clinicians rely on these descriptions to determine which biomarkers should be prioritized in screening, and healthcare providers use this information to shape public messaging about diet and medication. Further, epidemiologists need these findings as a baseline for evaluating causal claims. If the connection between cholesterol and diagnosed heart disease is weak after considering age and blood pressure, it calls for a reexamination of current guidelines and an exploration of the variables that truly matter. 

Our research question is: **What is the relationship between serum cholesterol (mg/dL) and heart disease, and how does this relationship change after adjusting for age and resting blood pressure?** We aim to outline the joint distribution of these variables without trying to establish a causal mechanism or create a deployable predictor.

## Data

We use the UCI Heart Disease dataset compiled by Janosi et al. (1988) and stored in the UCI Machine Learning Repository. This repository includes data from four clinical sites: the Cleveland Clinic Foundation, the Hungarian Institute of Cardiology, the V.A. Medical Center in Long Beach, and University Hospital in Zurich. The Cleveland subset (n = 304 before cleaning) is most studied and has the fewest missing values, thus being our main dataset. We also replicate key analyses on the combined four-site dataset (n = 920 before cleaning) to check for general applicability. Each observation represents a single patient visit, and each row includes patient demographics, measurements taken at rest, and results from angiographic exams. The original `num` variable records the extent of narrowing in vessels on a scale from 0 to 4. We convert this to a binary indicator (`heart_disease = 1` if `num > 0`, otherwise 0), in line with the binary outcome used in previous studies of this dataset. **Operationalization.** Our primary predictor *X* is `chol`, which measures serum cholesterol in mg/dL from a fasting blood draw. Our outcome, *Y*, is the binary heart disease indicator mentioned earlier. We include `age` (in years) and `trestbps` (which is resting blood pressure in mmHg) as covariates in our adjusted models. We exclude Cleveland observations with missing or unrealistic cholesterol values (coded as `?` or 0) and blood pressure values, resulting in **n = `r nrow(heart_cle)`** for the Cleveland analysis. The pooled four-site dataset has **n = `r nrow(heart_all)`** after applying the same filters. Since the Cleveland dataset is large, we split it into a 70/30 ratio for exploration and confirmation. All modeling decisions, such as variable selection and operationalization, were based solely on the 30% exploration set. All numbers reported in this document, including summaries, coefficients, and p-values, come from the 70% **confirmation set** (n = `r nrow(heart_confirm)`). 

**Limitations.** 

The binary outcome does not capture details about the severity of the disease. A linear probability model for a binary outcome can produce predicted values outside the [0, 1] range, but this is usually not extreme in practice. The dataset consists of a clinical convenience sample of higher-risk patients referred for angiography, meaning the heart disease rate (~47%) is much higher than in the general population. Therefore, estimates should not be directly applied to the broader population prevalence.

