URL: [https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/45/heart+disease](https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/45/heart+disease)

**2. Model Specifications Tried.**

| Specification | What We Learned |
|---|---|
| `heart_disease ~ chol` (Cleveland) | Baseline; chol coefficient positive but not significant (p ≈ 0.26) |
| `heart_disease ~ chol + age + trestbps` (Cleveland) | Adding age drives R² up; chol becomes smaller and still insignificant |
| `heart_disease ~ chol` (All four sites) | Larger n makes chol significant, but effect size unchanged |
| `heart_disease ~ chol + age + trestbps` (All four sites) | Both age and BP now significant; chol marginally significant |
| `heart_disease ~ log(chol) + age + trestbps` | Log transform did not improve residual pattern or interpretation; dropped |
| `heart_disease ~ chol + I(chol^2) + age + trestbps` | Squared term not significant; residuals showed no curvature; dropped |

**3. Residuals vs. Fitted Values Plot.**

```{r resid-plot, fig.cap="Residuals vs. fitted values for Model 2 (cholesterol + age + resting BP). Left: Cleveland confirmation set. Right: All four sites. The orange loess smoother tracks near zero with no systematic curvature, supporting the linear CEF assumption.", fig.width=7, fig.height=3}

make_resid <- function(model, df, title) {
  ggplot(data.frame(fitted    = fitted(model),
                    residuals = residuals(model)),
         aes(x = fitted, y = residuals)) +
    geom_point(alpha = 0.2, color = "steelblue", size = 1) +
    geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", color = "darkred") +
    geom_smooth(se = FALSE, color = "orange", linewidth = 0.8) +
    labs(title = title,
         x = "Fitted Values", y = "Residuals") +
    theme_minimal(base_size = 9) +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 9))
}

resid_cle <- make_resid(model2_cle, heart_confirm, "Cleveland Only")
resid_all <- make_resid(model2_all, heart_all,     "All Four Sites")

resid_cle + resid_all
```

